      "Veeravati was the only sister of seven loving brothers, married far from her parental home. When her first Karva Chauth arrived, she began the day-long fast without food or water, waiting for moonrise to complete the vow for her husband's long life.\n\nAs evening wore on, Veeravati grew faint from thirst and hunger, and her brothers could not bear to watch her suffer. Unable to wait for the true moon to rise over the horizon, they climbed a nearby hill and lit a fire behind a peepal tree, tricking their sister into believing the glow was the risen moon.\n\nBelieving the vow complete, Veeravati broke her fast — and at that very moment word came that her husband had died. Devastated, she wept through the night until the goddess Parvati appeared before her, gently revealing that she had been deceived and that the moon had not truly risen at all.\n\nParvati taught her to observe the fast again with full faith, sieve in hand, waiting through hunger and thirst until the true moon appeared in the sky. When Veeravati completed the vow properly, her husband was restored to life, and the household's joy became the model every wife since has followed.\n\nToday in Punjab, Haryana and Delhi, married women gather in circles at dusk to hear Veeravati's katha before they view the moon through a sieve and then their husband's face, renewing the same prayer that turned grief into life through patient, unbroken faith.",
